{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0113trpnG9YnJXDoityjfMSk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup:\n1. The MongoDB pods mount `mongodb-tls-cert` secret at `/etc/mongo-cert` and `mongodb-tls-ca` secret at `/etc/mongo-ca`\n2. MongoDB uses `server.pem` from `mongodb-tls-cert` (which contains both cert and key concatenated)\n3. The current server cert (`mongodb-tls-cert`) expires on 2026-06-27 (2 days from now)\n4. The CA is in `mongodb-tls-ca` with `ca.crt` and `ca.key`\n5. I'll use the openssl-toolbox pod to generate a new private key and CSR, then sign it with the existing CA to create the updated server.pem, and finally patch the `mongodb-tls-cert` secret with the new certificate\n\nSince Kubernetes automatically updates mounted secrets, I need to verify whether MongoDB 6.0 supports hot-reloading TLS certificates or if a rolling restart of the pods is necessary.\n\nLooking at the existing certificate's SANs to ensure the new one includes all the same DNS names: localhost, mongo, mongo.mongodb, mongo.mongodb.svc, mongo.mongodb.svc.cluster.local, and mongo.\n\nmongodb.svc.cluster.local with the stateful set pod names (mongo-rs-0, mongo-rs-1, mongo-rs-2). My plan is to copy the CA cert and key into the toolbox pod, generate a new key and CSR with these SANs, sign it with the CA, create the new server.pem, update the secret, and then do a rolling restart of the pods.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1907,"cache_read_input_tokens":35135,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1907},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0bb4f7bf-7fad-4c8f-a19e-54e7ea04441e","uuid":"9724f0db-3d41-4af1-ab94-c59aeb296da8","request_id